      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Brown meat and vegetables - Heat the oil over medium high heat in a large, deep skillet. Brown the ground meat, then add the chopped vegetables and sauté until softened.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Season and deglaze the pan - Sprinkle salt, paprika, pepper and flour over the pan. Cook for 2 minutes, stirring often. Stir in tomato paste and cook, stirring all the time, until it smells roasted (about 1 minute). Pour in the red wine (OR beef broth if you prefer!), scratching any browned bits off the bottom.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Finish filling and cool - Then stir in broth, herbs and peas, simmer 4-5 minutes and then let cool in a 7×11 inch baking dish.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Prep mash - In the meantime, make your favourite mashed potatoes. You need about 4 cups of mash to top off the casserole. About 1.5 pounds of peeled potatoes should yield enough.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Bake pie - Preheat the oven to 400°F (200°C). Spread the mashed potatoes over the cold filling. (Be careful not to mix up the two.) Criss-cross with a fork for a great look and crispy edges! Sprinkle with the cheese. Bake at 400°F for 20 minutes or until golden (I recommend baking on a lined baking sheet to catch any spills).",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Make ahead instructions - Assemble the entire pie as directed in the recipe, right up to the final baking step. Cover and refrigerate for up to 3 days, then bake at 400°F for 30-40 minutes, or until the filling is bubbly and the top is golden.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Freezer instructions",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Prepare as directed in the recipe, right up to the final baking step. Wrap well with foil and then aluminium foil. Label and freeze for up to 2 months.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "To reheat: No need to defrost! Remove both foils, then replace the aluminium foil. Bake at 400°F with the foil on for 1 hour. Remove the foil and bake for another 10 minutes, until browned.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Drain juicy fruit, toss with a tablespoon of cornflour, or blind-bake the base before filling. A sprinkle of semolina on the base soaks up stray juice.",
              "cause": "Filling too wet, or no blind-bake.",
              "symptom": "Pastry base went soggy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Rub butter into flour to coarse breadcrumb texture, then chill the mix before scattering. Keep clumps the size of peas for crunch.",
              "cause": "Butter melted in fully before baking.",
              "symptom": "Crumble topping went sandy, not crunchy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use a deeper dish next time and bake on a tray to catch drips.",
              "cause": "Tin too small, or too much liquid.",
              "symptom": "Filling spilled over the edges"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Let chilled pies sit at room temperature for 20 minutes before baking. Bake on the middle shelf at 180°C.",
              "cause": "Tin too cold from the fridge, or oven too hot.",
              "symptom": "Top browned but middle is cold"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Mixed fruit: use whatever's in season, apple plus blackberry, plum plus pear, rhubarb plus strawberry.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Nutty crumble: replace 30 g of the flour with rolled oats or chopped almonds.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Best fresh. Leftovers keep two days in the fridge; reheat covered with a splash of liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A British home cook's dish. It sits among the recipes families remember without thinking about, the kind that gets adjusted across generations and never quite the same twice.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
